    </exploration>


    <exploration xml:id="challenge-nonmaximal-prime">
      <title>Challenge</title>
      <p>
        <statement> Find a commutative ring , <m>R</m>, and a nonmaximal prime ideal <m>P</m> of <m>
          R</m>. </statement>

      </p>
      <solution>
        <p> In <m>\Z[x]</m>, it is straightforward to see that <m>(x)</m> is prime (<m>\Z/(x)\cong
          \Z</m>). Moreover, <m>(x)\subsetneq (2,x)</m>, and thus is not maximal. </p>
      </solution>
    </exploration>

  </subsection>

  <exercises xml:id="exers_principalIdealDomains">
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Mark the following as true or false.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>F</m> be a field, then <m>F[x]</m> is a PID.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>F</m> be a field, then <m>F[x,y]</m> is a PID.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The ring of integers is a PID.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The domain <m>\Z[x]</m> is a PID.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Every prime ideal is maximal.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Every maximal ideal is prime.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Every prime ideal is maximal in a PID.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Every irreducible element in a ring is prime.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Every irreducible element in a PID is prime.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find an integer <m>d</m> such that <m>I = (d)\subseteq \Z</m>, if
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>I = (4,10) = \{4x+10y\mid x,y\in\Z\}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>I = (6,7) = \{6s+7t\mid s,t\in\Z\}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>I = (9,12) =  \{9w+12z\mid w,z\in\Z\}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>I = (a,b) =  \{am+bn\mid m,n\in\Z\}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
          You do not need to prove that each of the sets above are ideals
          (though you should make sure you can do it).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>I</m> be an ideal in the ring <m>\mathbb{F}_2[x]</m>. Find a polynomial <m>d(x)</m> such that <m>I = (d(x))</m>, if
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>I = (x+1,x^2+1) = \{(x+1)p(x)+(x^2+1)q(x)\mid p(x),q(x)\in\mathbb{F}_2[x]\}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>I = (x+1,x^2+x+1) = \{(x+1)p(x)+(x^2+x+1)q(x)\mid p(x),q(x)\in\mathbb{F}_2[x]\}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>I = (x^4+x,x^3+x) =  \{(x^4+x)p(x)+(x^3+x)q(x)\mid p(x),q(x)\in\mathbb{F}_2[x]\}</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
          You do not need to prove that each of the sets above are ideals
          (though you should make sure you can do it).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>I</m> be a non-zero ideal in <m>\Z</m>. Show that <m>I=(d)</m>, where <m>d</m> is the greatest common divisor of all the non-zero elements of <m>I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>I</m> be a non-zero ideal in <m>F[x]</m> where <m>F</m> is a field. Show that <m>I=(d(x))</m>, where <m>d(x)</m> is a greatest common divisor of all the non-zero elements of <m>I</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine if the following ideals in the corresponding ring are prime and/or maximal or neither.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>R=\Z,\ I = (57)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>R=\Z,\ I = (31)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>R=\Z[x],\ I = (x-1)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>R=\Z[x],\ I = (x,2)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
