              <m>R=\Z[x,y], I=(x^2,2)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>R=\Z[x,y], I = (x,7)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a domain and <m>\mathfrak{p}=(p)</m> a principal ideal. Prove the converse of <xref ref="thm_primeElementGeneratesPrimeIdeal"/>. That is, prove that 
          if <m>\mathfrak{p}</m> is a prime ideal, then <m>p</m> is a prime element.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that the homomorphism in <xref ref="ex_nonprincipalPrimeIdeal"/> is in fact a homomorphism and is onto.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Generalize <xref ref="ex_nonprincipalPrimeIdeal"/> by showing that the <m>(x,m)</m> in <m>\Z[x]</m> is prime if and only if <m>m\in\mathbb{Z}</m> is a prime number.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the principal ideal <m>\mathfrak{p}=(x^2+y^2+1)</m> in <m>\R[x,y]</m>. Prove that <m>\mathfrak{p}</m> is prime but not maximal. Hint: Show that <m>\mathfrak{m}=(\mathfrak{p},x)</m> is a larger 
          ideal that is still proper.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>\R[x,y]/(x^2+y^2+1,x)\cong \C</m> so that the ideal <m>\mathfrak{m}</m> from the previous example is a maximal ideal containing <m>\mathfrak{p}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>\mathbb{F}_2[x]/(x^2+x+1)</m> is a field. Then write out the multiplication and addition tables.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>\mathbb{F}_3[x]/(x^2+x+1)</m> is not a field but <m>\mathbb{F}_3[x]/(x^2+1)</m> is a field. Write out the multiplication and addition tables for the latter.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring. Prove that the zero ideal <m>(0)</m> is prime if and only if <m>R</m> is a domain.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="exer_divisionAlgorithmGaussianIntegers">
      <title>Division Algorithm for Gaussian Integers</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>\Z[i]</m> be the Gaussian integers. Given <m>\alpha,\beta\in\Z[i]</m>, not both zero, show there exists (not necessarily unique) <m>\kappa,\rho\in\Z[i]</m> with
          <me>
            \alpha = \beta\kappa + \rho
          </me>
          where <m>N(\rho)\lt N(\beta)</m>. Here, <m>N(a+bi) = a^2+b^2</m>. Do so as follows:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Divide <m>\alpha</m> by <m>\beta</m> in <m>\C</m> to get <m>\alpha/\beta = x+iy</m> where <m>x,y\in\mathbb{Q}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Choose integers <m>m,n\in\Z</m> such that <m>|x-m|,|y-n|\leq\frac{1}{2}</m>. Then argue
              <me>
                N(x+iy-(m+in))\leq 1/2.
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Show that if <m>\kappa=m+in</m> and <m>\rho=\alpha-\beta\kappa</m>, then
              <me>
                \alpha = \beta\kappa+\rho
              </me>
              and
              <me>
                N(\rho)\lt N(\beta).
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>\Z[i]</m> is a PID by:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>I</m> be a non-zero ideal. Show there exists an element <m>\alpha\in I</m> of minimal norm. Here, the norm is <m>N(a+bi)=a^2+b^2</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Argue that <m>(\alpha)\subseteq I</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              For the reverse containment, use the division algorithm for <m>\Z[i]</m> in the previous problem. 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Deduce that <m>\Z[i]</m> is a PID.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>(x^2+x+1)</m> is a prime ideal in <m>\Q[x]</m>. Identify <m>\Q[x]/(x^2+x+1)</m> with a subfield of <m>\C</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>(x^4+x^3+x^2+1)</m> is a prime ideal in <m>\Q[x]</m>. Identify <m>\Q[x]/(x^4+x^3+x^2+x+1)</m> with a subfield of <m>\C</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that if <m>I=(a+bi)</m> is prime, then <m>\Z[i]/I\cong \mathbb{F}_m</m> where <m>m=N(a+bi) = a^2+b^2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find all ideals <m>J\subsetneq\mathbb{Z}[x]</m> such that <m>(x)\subsetneq J\subsetneq \mathbb{Z}[x]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>

